(8, 'A Quick Summary of Current Fair Trade Pricing', 'a-quick-summary-of-current-fair-trade-pricing', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 10pt"><font color="#443f3f" face="helvetica"><font style="font-size: 14pt;"><font>The\r\nbasic aim of the&nbsp;</font></font><font color="#443f3f"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>Transparent\r\nTrade Coffee</i></font></font><font color="#443f3f"><font style="font-size: 14pt;">&nbsp;program\r\nis to address the issue of appropriate compensation for farmers who\r\ngrow beans for roasters selling into the specialty coffee segment.</font></font></font></font></span></p>', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font><font color="#443f3f" face="helvetica" size="4"><font><font>The\r\nbasic aim of the&nbsp;</font></font><font color="#443f3f"><font><i>Transparent\r\nTrade Coffee</i></font></font><font color="#443f3f"><font>&nbsp;program\r\nis to address the issue of appropriate compensation for farmers who\r\ngrow beans for roasters selling into the specialty coffee segment.</font></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="color: rgb(68, 63, 63); line-height: 0.25in;"><font><font face="Times, serif" size="4"><br></font></font></font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font face="helvetica" size="4"><font style="color: rgb(68, 63, 63); line-height: 0.25in;"><font><font>Of\r\ncourse, there is a high-profile precedent for coffee markets\r\ndeveloping ways to let customers to know how farmers are compensated\r\n‚Äì the&nbsp;Fair Trade&nbsp;program. However, despite the growing\r\nawareness of&nbsp;Fair Trade&nbsp;coffee, it is surprising how few\r\ncoffee consumers know the actual prices that are paid to the\r\ncooperatives that represent coffee farmers. Under&nbsp;</font></font></font><a href="http://www.fairtrade.net/fileadmin/user_upload/content/2009/standards/documents/150311_EN_MainChanges_coffee.pdf" style="line-height: 0.25in;"><font color="#3a3091"><font>current\r\nrules</font></font></a><font color="#443f3f" style="color: rgb(68, 63, 63); line-height: 0.25in;"><font><font>&nbsp;(updated\r\nin 2011), the&nbsp;Fair Trade&nbsp;price floor for one pound of green\r\ncoffee is $1.40 ‚Äì plus a $0.20 social premium and another $0.30 if\r\nthe coffee is certified organic. This sums to $1.90 per pound of\r\ncertified Fair Trade Organic (FTO) coffee.</font></font></font></font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 10pt">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 10pt"><font color="#443f3f"><font style="font-size: 14pt;"><font face="helvetica">Historically\r\n(and importantly), the&nbsp;Fair Trade&nbsp;program has provided\r\ncritical&nbsp;insurance&nbsp;for participating coffee farmers in\r\nmarkets that are dominated by extreme price pressures. The question\r\nthat we are asking is whether it offers appropriate support for\r\nfarmers who participate in specialty markets.&nbsp;After all, how\r\n‚Äúfair‚Äù is it to pay a farmer $1.90 for coffee that ultimately\r\nsells for, say, $16.00?&nbsp;</font></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 10pt">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 10pt"><font color="#443f3f"><font style="font-size: 14pt;"><font face="helvetica">http://www.fairtrade.net/fileadmin/user_upload/content/2009/standards/documents/150311_EN_MainChanges_coffee.pdf</font></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 10pt"><font color="#443f3f" face="helvetica"><font color="#443f3f"><font style="font-size: 14pt;"><br></font></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 10pt"><font color="#443f3f" face="helvetica"><font color="#443f3f"><font style="font-size: 14pt;"><br></font></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 10pt"><font color="#443f3f" face="helvetica"><font color="#443f3f"><font style="font-size: 14pt;"><br></font></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 10pt"><font color="#443f3f" face="helvetica"><font color="#443f3f"><font style="font-size: 14pt;"><br></font></font></font></font></span></p>', NULL, '2014-04-08 07:29:12', 9),
(9, 'Thinking about a Specialty Coffee Retail Price Index‚Ä¶', 'thinking-about-a-specialty-coffee-retail-price-index', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">In\r\na previous post, we talked about how important Fair Trade minimum and\r\nNew York ‚ÄúC‚Äù prices are to the farmers who grow beans for\r\nspecialty coffee markets. A core problem is that one of these\r\nbenchmark prices is relatively low, while the other is often low and\r\nhighly volatile.</font></font></font></span></p>', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 14pt;"><font color="#443f3f" face="helvetica">In\r\na previous post, we talked about how important Fair Trade minimum and\r\nNew York ‚ÄúC‚Äù prices are to the farmers who grow beans for\r\nspecialty coffee markets. A core problem is that one of these\r\nbenchmark prices is relatively low, while the other is often low and\r\nhighly volatile.</font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="helvetica">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f" face="helvetica">What\r\nif another benchmark price was allowed to enter into negotiations for\r\ngreen coffee purchases; a price index that reflects the current\r\nprices paid for roasted specialty coffees?</font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="helvetica">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f" face="helvetica">To\r\ncreate such an index, we are developing a list of 60 ‚Äúblue chip‚Äù\r\ncoffee roasters; those that set standards in the North American\r\nspecialty coffee market. We are focusing on roasters whose coffees\r\nreceive the lion‚Äôs share of attention from Coffee Review, and those\r\nwho receive many of the Good Food Awards and Roast Magazine Awards.\r\nThe roasters that make up the current Specialty Coffee Retail Price\r\nIndex (SCRPI) received about 60% of the more than 1,500 coffee\r\nreviews published up to early 2014, and more than 70% of the Good\r\nFood and Roast Magazine awards during the same period.</font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="helvetica">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f" face="helvetica">The\r\nlist is also balanced in terms of geography, with 10% coming from\r\nCanada and 42% coming from the more coffee-obsessed western United\r\nStates. We are also ensuring that Fair Trade roasters are\r\nappropriately represented. Twenty of the 60 roasters in the current\r\nSCPRI index are listed on the Fair Trade USA or FairTrade Canada\r\nwebsites: (INSERT IMAGES).</font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="helvetica">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font face="helvetica"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 14pt;"><font color="#443f3f">To\r\ncapture both ends of the specialty coffee market, we visited the\r\nwebsite of each SCRPI roaster in June, 2014 and recorded information\r\nabout their lowest and highest-priced coffees (again, ignoring the\r\nvery high-priced Blue Mountain, Kona, Geisha/Esmeralda and Civet/Kopi\r\nLuwak coffees)</font></font></span><span style="color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-size: 14pt; line-height: 0.25in;">We\r\nthen compared these prices to those recorded in (roughly) December,\r\n2013:(INSERT IMAGES)</span></font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f" face="helvetica"><br></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f" face="helvetica">June,\r\n2014 prices at the low end of the specialty coffee market held steady\r\nat $12.01 per 12-ounce bag (down 0.12% from December, 2013). Prices\r\nat the top end of the market declined slightly to $17.23 per 12-ounce\r\nbag (down 2.74% from December, 2013).</font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font style="font-size: 14pt;"><font color="#443f3f" face="helvetica">It\r\nwill be interesting to see what happens when the next set of prices\r\nare pulled in September, 2014. It will be doubly interesting to see\r\nhow this (higher and seemingly stable) price index might become part\r\nof the negotiations for specialty coffee beans grown in future coffee\r\nharvests.</font></font></span></p>\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><br></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><br></p>', NULL, '2014-06-10 07:33:23', 8),
(10, 'Where Does Our Coffee Money Go', 'where-does-our-coffee-money-go', '	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">It\r\nis widely-known that coffee is the second-most traded commodity in\r\nthe world by value (</font></font></font><font color="#3a3091"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.investorguide.com/article/11836/what-are-the-most-commonly-traded-commodities-igu/">after\r\noil</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">).</font></font></font></span></p>', '	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">It\r\nis widely-known that coffee is the second-most traded commodity in\r\nthe world by value (</font></font></font><font color="#3a3091"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.investorguide.com/article/11836/what-are-the-most-commonly-traded-commodities-igu/">after\r\noil</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">).\r\nThis point is made clearly by the&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#3a3091"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.ico.org/coffee_story.asp">International\r\nCoffee Organization</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">:</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font color="#443f3f">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt">The\r\nimportance of coffee to the world economy cannot be overstated. It is\r\none of the most valuable primary products in world trade, in many\r\nyears second in value only to oil as a source of foreign exchange to\r\nproducing countries. Its cultivation, processing, trading,\r\ntransportation and marketing provide employment for hundreds of\r\nmillions of people worldwide.&nbsp;</font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><b><font color="#443f3f">Coffee\r\nis crucial to the economies and politics of many developing\r\ncountries; for many of the world''s Least Developed Countries, exports\r\nof coffee account for more than 50 percent of their foreign exchange\r\nearnings.</font></b></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">‚Äù</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Because\r\nof its importance to the people that live and work in the developing\r\nworld, we thought we‚Äôd paint a simple but powerful picture of the\r\ngeneral economic conditions in the countries that grow our specialty\r\ncoffees. To do this, we turn to a recently-develo</font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#000000">ped&nbsp;database&nbsp;</font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">of\r\nNorth American coffee roasters and prices, and to an\r\ninteresting&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#3a3091"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.coffeereview.com/">website</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;that\r\nposts a large number of quality reviews for specialty coffees. Here\r\nis a list of the countries that are featured most often in these two\r\ndata sources: (INSERT IMAGES)</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Then,\r\nwe gather some&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#3a3091"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GNP.PCAP.PP.CD">World\r\nBank data</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;to\r\ndetermine average per capita income levels for each of these\r\ncountries in 2012. The results are striking.&nbsp;</font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><b><font color="#443f3f">All\r\nspecialty-coffee producing countries (with the exception of the\r\nUnited States) are extremely poor.</font></b></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">This\r\nsuggests that as we become comfortable spending more money for the\r\ngreat coffees that are coming from countries like Ethiopia,\r\nIndonesia, Kenya, Colombia, Brazil and Guatemala, we must also ensure\r\nthat more of that money stays in these coffee-producing countries.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">In\r\nthis spirit, we close this insight with a simple thought experiment.\r\nThe average retail price per 12-ounce bag for the 85 Nicaragua\r\ncoffees in these two databases is $13.56. If we were able to ensure\r\nthat the coffee farmer gets 30% of this price, then her family would\r\nreceive an average of $4.07, which translates into roughly $4.60 per\r\ngreen pound of coffee. This is a $2.70 improvement over&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#3a3091"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.farmersto40.com/blog/2014/4/8/is-fair-trade-really-fair">current\r\nminimum Fair Trade prices</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">.\r\nAt this higher price, which is simply appropriate compensation for\r\ngrowing excellent coffee, every 1,000 pounds of specialty coffee that\r\nis grown and then sold in North America would bring an additional\r\n$2,700 into the Nicaragua economy. This increase equals 65% of its\r\ncurrent average GNI per capita.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">We\r\nare not saying that this is an easy change to make, but it is one\r\npromising way to alleviate the extreme poverty that we are seeing in\r\ncoffee-producing countries around the world.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br>\r\n\r\n</p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"></p>', NULL, '2014-07-21 09:00:06', 9),
(11, 'Bird Rock Roasters - More Transparency Data', 'bird-rock-roasters-more-transparency-data', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">We\r\nhave been analyzing ‚Äì wherever possible ‚Äì information about the\r\nshares of posted retail coffee prices that make it back to the\r\nfarmers who grow the beans. Here, we continue these matched analyses\r\nof green and roasted coffee prices by looking at the 2014 Direct\r\nTrade Transparency Report published by Bird Rock Coffee Roasters.</font></font></font></span></p>', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">We\r\nhave been analyzing ‚Äì wherever possible ‚Äì information about the\r\nshares of posted retail coffee prices that make it back to the\r\nfarmers who grow the beans. Here, we continue these matched analyses\r\nof green and roasted coffee prices by looking at the 2014 Direct\r\nTrade Transparency Report published by Bird Rock Coffee Roasters.&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">This\r\nis a detailed and honest account of the economic terms of trade\r\nbetween Bird Rock and its Direct Trade farmers. In it, coffee\r\ndrinkers are reminded that ‚Äúthe price paid to the broker is not the\r\nprice paid to the farmer.&nbsp;The broker‚Äôs price includes all\r\nassociated costs of import/export, storage, not to mention the costs\r\nthat broker had to pay to source the coffee at origin in the first\r\nplace on top of the margin that the broker takes ‚Äî which can be\r\nanywhere from 20 cents a pound to over $1/pound for some brokers.‚Äù\r\nThis point is critical because most specialty coffee is sourced\r\nthrough brokers. We are also reminded that ‚Äúthis does not represent\r\na farmer‚Äôs profit since there is the cost to grow, harvest and mill\r\nthe coffee.‚Äù</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Bird\r\nRock‚Äôs 2014 Transparency Report provides green coffee price\r\ninformation for fourteen coffees sourced from farms in El Salvador,\r\nGuatemala, Nicaragua and Panama in early 2014. Each price figure\r\nrepresents ‚Äúthe price we paid for the coffee Freight on Board\r\n(FOB), which signifies the price for coffee after milling but before\r\nexport; the final price negotiated with the grower.‚Äù</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Our\r\non-line search processes (which rely on the&nbsp;Wayback Machine&nbsp;for\r\ninformation about coffees that are not currently available for sale)\r\nplus email exchanges with Bird Rock owners ‚Äì turned up matching\r\nretail prices for eleven of these coffees.*&nbsp;After converting\r\nposted retail prices to green-pound equivalents, we are able to\r\ncompare them to their corresponding green coffee prices.**(IMAGE HERE)</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">On\r\naverage, Bird Rock‚Äôs green coffee prices represent 32.3% of the\r\nretail prices that they charge coffee drinkers. However, this figure\r\nis influenced by a few outliers, including two geisha coffees sourced\r\nfrom Panama at $50 and $55 per green pound! If we look instead at the\r\nmedian share of retail prices going to farmers, we get a figure of\r\n20.9%, which is almost identical to the share reported in a similar\r\nanalysis of Counter Culture‚Äôs 2012 Transparency Report.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Given\r\nthat these are the (only?) two U.S.-based roasters that go out of\r\ntheir way to post detailed transparency reports that include prices\r\npaid to specific growers on their own websites, it might be fair to\r\nconclude that paying farmers an average of roughly 20% of posted\r\nretail prices represents current best practice in the specialty\r\ncoffee sector. Of course, we will be more certain of this claim as\r\nmore roasters follow the lead of Bird Rock Coffee Roasters and\r\nCounter Culture and tell their customers exactly how much they are\r\npaying their growers for green coffee beans.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="2" style="font-size: 11pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">*\r\nPrices charged to individuals buying coffee in-store may be different\r\nfrom those charged to on-line buyers. To maximize comparability\r\nacross analyses, we only present on-line prices.</font></i></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="2" style="font-size: 11pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">**\r\nGreen pound equivalent prices are calculated by converting posted\r\nretail prices to one-pound equivalents and then assuming 15%\r\nshrinkage during the roasting process. In this way, the green pound\r\nequivalent for the Elida Estate coffee from Panama equals $25.99\r\ntimes (16 ounces / 12 ounces) times 85%; or $29.46.</font></i></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font color="#443f3f">\r\n&nbsp;</font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br>\r\n\r\n</p>', NULL, '2015-03-15 09:06:36', 6),
(12, 'Transparency at Starbucks?', 'transparency-at-starbucks', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">A\r\n2013 Roast Magazine story that discusses transparency in the\r\nspecialty coffee market briefly mentions Starbucks</font></font></font></span></p>', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font color="#443f3f">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt">For\r\ncoffee verified to meet their Coffee and Farmer Equity (C.A.F.E.)\r\nPractices standards, the company says financial transparency ‚Äúdown\r\nto the farmworker level‚Äù is a must ‚Ä¶ [however], the furthest\r\nStarbucks goes in disclosing financial information is to give an\r\naverage purchase price for their green coffee ($2.38 per pound in\r\n2011); they don‚Äôt report about individual purchases.‚Äù</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">This\r\ninconsistency compelled us to look more closely at Starbucks‚Äô\r\nsourcing practices. According to Starbucks, transparency is guided by\r\nits Coffee and Farmer Equity (C.A.F.E.) program, which ‚Äúensures\r\ncoffee quality while promoting social, economic and environmental\r\nstandards.‚Äù Under this model, ‚Äúeconomic transparency is required.\r\nSuppliers must submit evidence of payments made throughout the coffee\r\nsupply chain to demonstrate how much of the price that we pay for\r\ngreen coffee gets to the farmer.‚Äù</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">This\r\nin-house certification program yielded the following summary of their\r\n2014 performance: (INSERT IMAGE)</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Although\r\nthis suggests a small improvement between 2013 and 2014, it does not\r\nreveal how much Starbucks pays for its green coffee. For this, you\r\nhave to dig a little deeper to learn that ‚ÄúStarbucks paid an\r\naverage price of $1.72 per pound in 2014.‚Äù According to previous\r\nreports, Starbucks paid an average of $1.92 per pound in 2013, and\r\n$2.56 per pound in 2012. These three numbers, combined with\r\nhistorical information about what Starbucks charged its (on-line)\r\ncustomers for its French, Verona, Sumatra and Pike Place coffees in\r\n2012, 2013 and 2014, generate the following graph: (INSERT IMAGE)</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">The\r\neffective share of roasted coffee prices that went to purchasing\r\ngreen beans ‚Äì which probably includes the (unreported) amount that\r\nwent to middlemen ‚Äì dropped from 23.7% in 2012 to 15.9% in 2014.\r\nGiven the total volume of coffee purchased by Starbucks in 2014 (a\r\nreported 461 million pounds), and this two-year green price reduction\r\nof 84 cents per pound, Starbucks seems to have removed more than $387\r\nmillion from coffee-growing countries over a two year period (unless\r\nthe reported green price reduction came from squeezing the\r\nmiddlemen).</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">We\r\nrecognize these numbers and calculations might be incomplete because\r\nwe do not know how much of the money that Starbucks spends on green\r\ncoffee actually goes to growers. This is unfortunate because the\r\nclaims associated with the C.A.F.E. program suggest that these\r\nnumbers are made available by Starbucks‚Äô suppliers ‚Äì and, we\r\nwould argue, should be disclosed to consumers ‚Äì for 96% of the\r\ngreen coffee purchased in 2014.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">We\r\nalso recognize that the price paid for green beans is not the only\r\nway that roasters support coffee farmers. For example, Starbucks\r\ncontributed $16.3 million in 2014 to support loans to farmers through\r\nRoot Capital (and other partners). However, we should consider that\r\nthe economic value of pre-harvest financing to a farmer is increasing\r\nin the price that he or she gets when the coffee is sold. Thus, to\r\nget a complete picture of these other farm-based programs, we must\r\nsee the more detailed price numbers (and must see them trending in\r\nthe right direction).</font></font></font></span></p>', NULL, '2015-04-06 09:08:45', 9),
(13, 'Specialty Coffee Prices and the Commodity Market', 'specialty-coffee-prices-and-the-commodity-market', '	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">It\r\nis refreshing to hear that a number of roasters are looking for ways\r\nto divorce negotiations for green specialty coffee from the\r\nvolatility that plagues the commodity market.</font></font></font></span></p>', '	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">It\r\nis refreshing to hear that a number of roasters are looking for ways\r\nto divorce negotiations for green specialty coffee from the\r\nvolatility that plagues the commodity market. (INSERT IMAGE)</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">To\r\nstimulate these efforts, we provide some preliminary observations\r\nthat indicate how retail prices for specialty coffees are already\r\ndivorced from this volatility. To do this, we gather the\r\n(refreshingly accessible) price and quality information posted on\r\nthe&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.coffeereview.com/">Coffee\r\nReview</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;website.</font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 11pt"><font color="#443f3f">1</font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Starting\r\nwith coffees that were on the market and reviewed during the 2010 to\r\n2014 period, we set aside what might be called "elite coffees"\r\n(i.e., those from Hawaii and Jamaica; the geishas and civet coffees;\r\nand the other coffees that sold for more than $60 per pound). This\r\nleaves 696 coffees that report both retail price and coffee quality\r\ninformation.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">The\r\nfirst thing to note is that these are, on average, excellent coffees;\r\nwith cupping scores averaging 91.5 across the five years. (INSERT IMAGE)</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Because\r\nthe Coffee Review conducts and posts its reviews monthly, we can\r\nmatch each review in the data to the corresponding monthly average of\r\nthe&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.ico.org/prices/p2.htm">ICO\r\nComposite Price</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">,\r\nwhich captures movements in the global commodity coffee market.</font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="2" style="font-size: 11pt"><font color="#443f3f">2</font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;The\r\nsecond figure shows that while retail coffee prices tended to drift\r\nupward over the five-year observation window, the ICO price has been\r\nconsiderably more variable.&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">The\r\nmore specific question that we tackle here is the extent to which cup\r\nquality and the prevailing ICO price influence roasted coffee prices.\r\nTo do this, we estimate a (very simple) regression model that relates\r\nposted prices per pound to both of these variables.&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-size: 14pt; font-family: Helvetica, serif; line-height: 0.25in;"><br></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-size: 14pt; font-family: Helvetica, serif; line-height: 0.25in;">As\r\nyou can see, there is a positive and significant (p=0.00) effect of\r\ncoffee quality on posted prices. In fact, the 0.924 coefficient\r\nestimate suggests that each additional point awarded by the Coffee\r\nReview corresponds with a $0.93 bump in retail price.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">On\r\nthe other hand,&nbsp;</font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">there\r\nis no discernible effect of the current ICO price on retail coffee\r\nprices</font></i></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">.\r\nThe estimated coefficient (-0.249) is negative, but not statistically\r\nsignificant (p=0.68).</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">A\r\nlot more can (and should) be done with these kinds of data to ensure\r\nthat the effects presented in this post are robust. For now, however,\r\nit seems safe to assume that prices for roasted specialty coffee are\r\nbeing driven by cup quality (something that growers can influence),\r\nbut are</font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">unaffected\r\nby current commodity price</font></i></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">s.\r\nThus, it makes a lot of sense to liberate coffee growers from the\r\n(unrelated) volatility that plagues the commodity market. &nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><br></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-left: 0.42in; margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%">\r\n<span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 11pt"><font color="#443f3f">1.\r\nThe&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 11pt"><u><a href="http://www.coffeereview.com/about-us/">stated\r\naim</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 11pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;of\r\nthe Coffee Review is to ‚Äúentertain and educate coffee drinkers,\r\nfood service professionals, and the coffee trade with a credible and\r\neasy-to-use coffee guide based on objective, blind reviews from\r\nKenneth Davids and other experienced individuals in the specialty\r\ncoffee industry.‚Äù Between 1997 and 2014, the Coffee Review\r\nconducted and posted more than 2,000 reviews!</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-left: 0.42in; margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%">\r\n<font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-left: 0.42in; margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%">\r\n<span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 11pt"><font color="#443f3f">2.\r\nThe International Coffee Organization (ICO) is the main\r\nintergovernmental organization for coffee. It makes a practical\r\ncontribution to the development of a sustainable world coffee sector\r\nand to reducing poverty in developing countries by (among other\r\nthings) ‚Äú</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 11pt"><u><a href="http://www.ico.org/mission07_e.asp?section=About_Us">promoting\r\nmarket transparency by providing a wide range of statistics on the\r\nworld coffee sector.</a></u></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"></p>', NULL, '2015-04-22 09:10:51', 7);
