(14, 'Counter Culture - Two Years of Transparency Reports', 'counter-culture-two-years-of-transparency-reports', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font color="#443f3f">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>Roasters\r\nhave quite a bit of power to influence the kinds of questions\r\nconsumers are asking about coffee, and Counter Culture wants their\r\ncustomers to want transparency.‚Äù</i></font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">(Roast\r\nMagazine, Feb 2013)</font></font></font></span></p>', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">According\r\nto Roast Magazine‚Äôs story,&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.roastmagazine.com/resources/Articles/Roast_JanFeb13_TheLongPipe.pdf">The\r\nLong Pipe</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">,\r\n‚Äú</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="https://counterculturecoffee.com/">Counter\r\nCulture</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;is\r\none of the only coffee companies in the United States that produces\r\nan annual transparency report‚Äîone that curates complex data for\r\ncustomers so that it‚Äôs digestible while still being meaningful.‚Äù</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">In\r\neach of the past four years, these&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="https://counterculturecoffee.com/sustain/transparency-report">Transparency\r\nReports</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;provide\r\nspecific information about the coffees purchased as part of their\r\nDirect Trade program. They report on green coffee prices and cupping\r\nscores, as well as details about the buying relationships between\r\nCounter Culture and its coffee growers.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">This\r\npost begins with 38 coffees listings found in the 2012 and 2013\r\nTransparency Reports. Using the&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="https://archive.org/">Internet\r\nArchive</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">,\r\nwe went ‚Äúback in time‚Äù to locate and match retail sales\r\ninformation to 23 of these coffees (see the table below).</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">On\r\naverage, Counter Culture paid $3.47 per green pound for these\r\ncoffees. At the other end of the specialty coffee value chain, they\r\ncharged their (on-line) customers an average of $18.63 per green\r\npound equivalent. Thus, they returned an average of 18.4% of retail\r\ncoffee prices to their growers. The effective grower shares ranged\r\nfrom 10.5% (Las Milpas in 2013) to 25.9% (Ndaroini in 2012).</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Because\r\nthese reports provide information on a range of different coffees, we\r\ncan also report some additional summary statistics:</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><span style="color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-size: 14pt; font-family: Helvetica, serif; line-height: 0.25in;"><ul><li><span style="font-size: 14pt; line-height: 0.25in;">The\r\n	correlation between the green prices and cupping scores is positive\r\n	(?=0.37). This suggests that the growers working with Counter\r\n	Culture are compensated for producing higher coffee quality.&nbsp;</span><br></li><li><span style="font-size: 14pt; line-height: 0.25in;">The\r\n	correlation between green prices and the duration of the\r\n	relationships with Counter Culture is also positive (?=0.41). This\r\n	suggests that growers are rewarded economically for maintaining\r\n	durable trading relationships.</span><br></li></ul></span><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">These\r\nobservations indicate the value that comes with presenting just a few\r\ncritical pieces of information ‚Äì i.e., green coffee prices, cupping\r\nscores and year of first coffee purchase. With a few simple\r\ncalculations, these data can be transformed into observations and\r\ninsights that are critical to understanding the treatment of growers\r\nin specialty coffee markets.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">We\r\nconclude with one (big?) question. Given the clear commitment to\r\ntransparency and the desire to have customers take these numbers more\r\nseriously, can we effectively present this information to specialty\r\ncoffee consumers&nbsp;</font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><font color="#443f3f">when\r\nthey are making their purchase decisions</font></u></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">?</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="2" style="font-size: 11pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">1.\r\nAs is the case with&nbsp;</font></i></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="2" style="font-size: 11pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#!Bird-Rock-Roasters-More-Transparency-Data/cvxy/552207740cf21933cd3bf7b3">Bird\r\nRock‚Äôs Transparency Report</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="2" style="font-size: 11pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">,\r\nthese are f.o.b. prices paid to the growers themselves</font></i></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 11pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">2.\r\nGreen pound equivalent prices are calculated by converting posted\r\nretail prices to one-pound equivalents and then assuming 15%\r\nshrinkage during the roasting process. In this way, the green pound\r\nequivalent for the Concepci√≥n Huista coffee equals $15.50 times (16\r\nounces / 12 ounces) times 85%; or $17.57.</font></i></font></font></span></p>', NULL, '2015-05-06 09:14:05', 9),
(15, 'Fair Trade Proof Coffee Contracts ‚Äì 2010 to 2014', 'fair-trade-proof-coffee-contracts-2010-to-2014', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font color="#443f3f">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>Transparency\r\nmakes fairness possible because it makes hiding the truth\r\nimpossible.‚Äù</i></font></font></font></span></p>', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">As\r\nwe continue to think about transparency in&nbsp;specialty\r\ncoffee&nbsp;markets, it is important to point to another interesting\r\nsource of information about prices paid to coffee growers.&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.fairtradeproof.org/">Fair\r\nTrade Proof</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">(FTP)\r\nis ‚Äúa cooperative of independent roasters committed to Fair Trade\r\nas a long-term partnership between farmers and roasters.‚Äù</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">A\r\ncritical element of this partnership is a website that houses the\r\ncontracts that document hundreds of specialty coffee transactions.\r\nThe example copied here shows that 17,494 pounds of green coffee were\r\npurchased from&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.cecocafen.com.ni/">CECOCAFEN</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;(a\r\nNicaraguan coffee cooperative) in a contract that closed on February\r\n18, 2014. The price paid for this coffee was $2.21 per pound, which\r\nwas set based on the prevailing NY ‚ÄúC‚Äù price, plus premiums for\r\nFair Trade (20 cents), organic (30 cents) and bean quality (20\r\ncents).</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">For\r\nthis post, we compiled data from 361 contracts that closed between\r\n2010 and 2014. These contracts covered coffees produced in 15\r\ncountries by 32 cooperatives, and purchased by 25 different roasters.\r\nThe average contract was for 38,636 pounds of green coffee, and was\r\npriced at $2.78 per pound.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">The\r\nprices in 87% of these contracts were tied explicitly to the NY ‚ÄúC‚Äù\r\nprice. Thus, it is not surprising to see that that the year-to-year\r\naverage price in these contracts moves in tandem with the\r\ncorresponding&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.ico.org/coffee_prices.asp">ICO\r\nPrice</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">.\r\nIt is also important to note the consistent positive price\r\ndifferential in these contracts. Overall, they paid an average\r\npremium of $1.17 over the prevailing ICO Price; ranging from $1.00 in\r\n2010 to $1.25 in 2012.&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">In\r\na (simple) regression model that relates green prices to the\r\ncurrent-month ICO Price, the parameter estimate is positive and\r\nsignificant. Every $1.00 change in the ICO Price corresponds with a\r\n$1.09 change in prices paid to cooperatives. This is an important\r\ncontrast to the insignificant effect reported in&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#!Specialty-Coffee-Prices-and-the-Commodity-Market/cvxy/5537fdf20cf2adc1acde7ac7">a\r\nmodel that examines the effect of the ICO Price on roasted coffee\r\nprices</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">.</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Other\r\nparameters in this model suggest that green prices fall slightly as\r\nthe quantity of coffee purchased increases; prices are roughly 0.5\r\ncents per pound lower for every additional 1,000 pounds purchased.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">On\r\nthe other hand, prices tend to increase with the number of roasters\r\nparticipating in each contract. Moving from one (the minimum) to\r\ntwenty (the maximum) participating roasters corresponds with an\r\naverage price increase of roughly 17.5 cents per pound.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">The\r\ngeographic scope of these contracts tell us something about the\r\naverage prices paid to coffee growers in different countries.\r\nRelative to a small hold-out group that consists of coffees from\r\nBrazil, Dominican Republic, DR Congo, Ecuador and El Salvador there\r\nis a significant ‚ÄúColombia premium‚Äù of 20.1 cents per pound, an\r\n‚ÄúIndonesia premium‚Äù of 29.2 cents per pound, and an ‚ÄúEthiopia\r\npremium‚Äù of 67.6 cents per pound. There is also a significant\r\n‚ÄúHonduras discount‚Äù of 28.7 cents per pound, a ‚ÄúNicaragua\r\ndiscount‚Äù of 23.0 cents per pound, and a ‚ÄúPeru discount‚Äù of\r\n17.1 cents per pound.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">We\r\nclose this post with a request to FTP roasters. With a fair bit of\r\neffort, we were able to locate the web pages where 84 of the roasted\r\ncoffees covered by 2014 FTP contracts are sold. This allows us to\r\ntell the potential consumers of each coffee the green price paid and\r\nthe corresponding effective share of retail price going to the\r\ngrower. The final table in this post indicates that FTP roasters paid\r\nan average of $2.89 per green pound for these coffees, which\r\ntranslates into an average effective grower share of 22.9%.\r\nIndividually, our research suggests that:</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><font face="Helvetica, serif"><ul style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><li><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Cafe\r\n	Campesino‚Äôs&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.cafecampesino.com/Bolivia_Medium_Roast_Coffee_p/c106.htm">Bolivia\r\n	Medium Roast Coffee</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;was\r\n	sourced from Bolivia ‚Äì FECAFEB at $2.71 per green pound. The\r\n	roasted coffee sells for $12.95 per pound, which translates into an\r\n	effective grower share of 24.6%;</font></font></font><br></li><li><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Higher\r\n	Grounds‚Äô&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.highergroundstrading.com/cart/34/coffee/single-origin-coffees/organic-mexican-yachil-dark-roast">Organic\r\n	Mexican Yachil Dark Roast</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;was\r\n	sourced from Mexico ‚Äì Yachil at $2.74 per green pound. The roasted\r\n	coffee sells for $11.00 per 12-ounce bag, which translates into an\r\n	effective grower share of 21.9%; and</font></font></font></li><li><font style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in; color: rgb(68, 63, 63);"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Just\r\n	Coffee‚Äôs&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://shop.justcoffee.coop/collections/single-origin/products/sumatra-light-roasted-single-origin">Light\r\n	Sumatra</a></u></font></font></font><font style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in; color: rgb(68, 63, 63);"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;was\r\n	sourced from Indonesia - APKO/Askogo/Permata Gayo at $2.93 per green\r\n	pound. The roasted coffee sells for $14.00 per 12-ounce bag, which\r\n	translates into an effective grower share of 18.4%.</font></font></font></li></ul></font>\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">It\r\nwould be great to see these details confirmed and then posted to\r\nthe&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#!ttcoffees/cjg9">TT\r\nCoffees page</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;on\r\nthis site!</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 11pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">*\r\nGreen pound equivalent (GPE) retail prices are calculated by\r\nconverting posted prices to one-pound equivalents and then assuming\r\n15% shrinkage during the roasting process. In this way, the green\r\npound equivalent for the Colombia - Fondo Paez coffee from Amavida\r\nCoffee equals $14.50 times (16 ounces / 12 ounces) times 85%; or\r\n$16.43.</font></i></font></font></span></p>', NULL, '2015-05-19 09:16:56', 7),
(17, 'Cup of Excellence ‚Äì Five Years of Competition and Auction Data', 'cup-of-excellence-five-years-of-competition-and-auction-data', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">How\r\ngreen coffee markets can work better for growers‚Ä¶</font></i></font></font></span></p>', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="https://www.allianceforcoffeeexcellence.org/en/cup-of-excellence/">Cup\r\nof Excellence</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;(COE)\r\nprograms have been run in ten coffee-growing countries since as early\r\nas 1999. In these programs, many of the country‚Äôs top coffee\r\ngrowers compete for the attention and affirmation of the world‚Äôs\r\nmost discerning coffee tasters. After cuppings are completed, winning\r\ncoffees (roughly 25 per competition, on average) are auctioned off to\r\nglobal buyers that gather at each event.</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Thanks\r\nto COE organizers‚Äô commitment to transparency, we can see that the\r\naverage price per green pound paid at auction rose from $4.09 in 2005\r\nto $9.56 in 2014. We can also see how year-to-year movements in\r\naverage auction prices trace the average quality scores received at\r\nthe competitions. Winning bids were highest in 2013 ($10.03 per\r\npound), when the average cupping score was 87.5. Lower prices were\r\nobserved in 2011 ($7.23 per pound) when the average cupping score was\r\n86.6.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-size: 14pt; font-family: Helvetica, serif; line-height: 100%;"><br></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-size: 14pt; font-family: Helvetica, serif; line-height: 100%;">Country\r\nEffects</span></p>\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">When\r\nwe hone in on the last five years of the program ‚Äì 2010 to 2014 ‚Äì\r\nit is not as clear that auction prices always track cupping scores at\r\nthe country level. Over this period, auction prices were highest in\r\nGuatemala ($10.72 per pound), which had the lowest average cupping\r\nscore (86.8). At the other extreme, prices in Brazilian and\r\nNicaraguan auctions were quite low ($7.72 and $7.58 per pound)\r\ndespite high average cupping scores (87.5 and 87.4).</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">A\r\nSimple Regression Model</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">We\r\nuse these same five years of data to estimate a simple regression\r\nmodel that shows the country-of-origin effects, as well as an\r\nexpected trade-off between lot size (i.e., quantity) and price. For\r\nevery additional bag of coffee offered at auction, the winning bid\r\nfalls by an average of roughly 6.6 cents per pound.&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">The\r\nmodel also shows the positive and significant effect of cupping\r\nscores on prices. On average, each additional point awarded by\r\ncompetition judges corresponds with a $0.76 bump in the winning\r\nauction bid. However, auction participants are not only bidding on\r\ncoffee quality, but also competition rank. The rank coefficients in\r\nthe model suggest that winning coffees sold for an average premium of\r\n$17.43 per pound! Even fifth-ranked coffees sold for a modest price\r\npremium of $1.24 per pound.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Another\r\nvariable in the model counts the number of prior COE events held in\r\neach country. The positive coefficient on this variable suggests that\r\n‚Äì all else equal ‚Äì auction prices increase by roughly 15.5 cents\r\nevery time another COE competition is held in the country.&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Finally,\r\nbecause we know the month and year of each COE auction, we can match\r\nevery observation with the corresponding monthly average of the&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.ico.org/prices/p2.htm">ICO\r\nComposite Price</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">,\r\nwhich captures movements in the global commodity coffee market.&nbsp;\r\nThe model returns a&nbsp;</font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><u><font color="#443f3f">negative</font></u></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;ICO\r\nPrice coefficient. Unlike the positive effect observed in&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#!Fair-Trade-Proof-Coffee-Contracts-%E2%80%93-2010-to-2014/cvxy/555bb6580cf298b2d3ccf79a">a\r\nprevious analysis of Fair Trade Proof data</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">,\r\nCOE auction prices tend to run counter-cyclically with commodity\r\ncoffee prices.</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font size="4" style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">What\r\nCould All of this Mean?</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">These\r\nobservations seem to suggest that green coffee markets can work\r\nfairly well when real competition is introduced into the buying\r\nprocess. Quality is rewarded and prices trend upward as competition\r\nintensifies. However, several questions require further thought and\r\nmore analysis. For example:&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p><ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in">\r\n	<span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Why\r\n	are we seeing large average country differences in auction prices,\r\n	even after controlling for coffee quality? &nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n	</li><li>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in">\r\n	<span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">What\r\n	about the rest of the specialty coffee being produced each year, and\r\n	the coffee growers not featured in the COE auctions? After all, all\r\n	of the 2010 to 2014 COE auctions combined featured just 1,170 coffee\r\n	growers and 45,000 sacks of coffee.</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n	</li><li>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in">\r\n	<span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">For\r\n	these coffees and these growers, how can we restructure specialty\r\n	coffee markets so that quality-based competition drives all green\r\n	coffee negotiations toward prices fetched in COE auctions, as\r\n	opposed to the lower and highly-variable commodity prices?</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n</li></ul>\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">(One\r\nmight also ask what happens to the top-ranked COE coffees when they\r\nhit the retail market ‚Ä¶ we‚Äôll look at these prices in a future\r\npost. Stay tuned to&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/">www.transparenttradecoffee.org</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">.)</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 11pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">1.\r\nThese competition rank effects are consistent with those reported\r\nby&nbsp;</font></i></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 11pt"><i><u><a href="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/agec.12132/abstract">Wilson\r\nand Wilson</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 11pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;in\r\ntheir analysis of data covering the 2004 to 2010 period.</font></i></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 11pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">2.\r\nThe International Coffee Organization (ICO) is the main\r\nintergovernmental organization for coffee. It makes a practical\r\ncontribution to the development of a sustainable world coffee sector\r\nand to reducing poverty in developing countries by (among other\r\nthings) ‚Äú</font></i></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 11pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.ico.org/mission07_e.asp?section=About_Us">promoting\r\nmarket transparency by providing a wide range of statistics on the\r\nworld coffee sector</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 11pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">.‚Äù</font></i></font></font></span></p>', NULL, '2015-06-03 09:39:49', 9);
INSERT IGNORE INTO `ttc_posts` (`postID`, `postTitle`, `postSlug`, `postDesc`, `postCont`, `postImg`, `postDate`, `catID`) VALUES
(18, 'Talking About Transparency', 'talking-about-transparency', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">Perspectives\r\nfrom 26 specialty coffee roasters on the issue of pricing\r\ntransparency</font></i></font></font></span></p>', '\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/">Transparent\r\nTrade Coffee</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;(TTC)&nbsp;is\r\nworking to change specialty coffee market conversations and, in doing\r\nso, improve economic outcomes for coffee growers. We are doing this\r\nby emphasizing pricing transparency; anchoring all specialty coffee\r\nconversations on the prices paid to growers for their green coffee.</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">We\r\nare clearly not the first to talk about transparency. To provide a\r\nfeel for how different roasters are talking about pricing\r\ntransparency, we searched the websites of the&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#!roasters/clar">SCRPI\r\nRoasters</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;and\r\nlocated sentences that include the words ‚Äòtransparent‚Äô or\r\n‚Äòtransparency.‚Äô</font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 8pt"><font color="#443f3f">1</font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;In\r\nthe end, we found references to pricing transparency on the websites\r\nof 26 of the SCRPI Roasters.&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">To\r\nget a feel for what roasters are talking about when they talk\r\ntransparency, we invite readers to read through the following\r\nstructured presentation of these transparency statements, and to\r\nclick through each of the hyperlinks to get a better idea about the\r\ncontext of each statement.</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Some\r\nroasters offer fairly basic statements about transparency:</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><ul><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>Additionally,\r\n	public demand continues to increase for coffee that is ethical\r\n	and&nbsp;transparentto the source.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.1000facescoffee.com/blog/2014/12/14/coloring-in-the-wild">1000\r\n	Faces Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>In\r\n	addition to this&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;in price discovery we\r\n	sometimes pre-finance a producer ahead of the harvest.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://batdorfcoffee.com/blog/coffee/what-is-relationship-coffee/">Batdorf\r\n	&amp; Bronson</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>In\r\n	the last decade or two we‚Äôve seen the emergence of what has been\r\n	called the Third Wave of coffee ‚Äì a loosely defined movement\r\n	toward higher quality drinks, more differentiation\r\n	andtransparency&nbsp;around coffee as a seasonal product, and a\r\n	general reverence for many aspects of the craft.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="https://bluebottlecoffee.com/frequency/except-for-espresso">Blue\r\n	Bottle Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>De\r\n	La Paz isn‚Äôt the first coffee roaster in the world to focus\r\n	on&nbsp;transparent&nbsp;and seasonal blends.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="https://www.delapazcoffee.com/about/">De\r\n	La Paz Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>The\r\n	currency of leadership is truth and&nbsp;transparency.‚Äù\r\n	(</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="https://www.news.starbucks.com/2014annualmeeting/howard-schultz-2014-shareholders-speech">Starbucks</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>The\r\n	results of all this discussion and technology, as so many other\r\n	industries have experienced, are&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;and\r\n	traceability.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.zokacoffee.com/the_third_wave_in_its_third_year/">Zoka\r\n	Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li></ul></font>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Other\r\nroasters articulate the challenges associated with pricing\r\ntransparency:</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<span style="color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><ul><li><span style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú</span><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>Coffee\r\n	can change hands multiple times between the producer and the\r\n	consumer, makingtransparency&nbsp;difficult.‚Äù (Caribou Coffee)</i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>Roasters\r\n	seeking&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;regarding farming practices, farmer\r\n	income, and living standards must work extra hard to obtain\r\n	information and develop relationships on the ground.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.equatorcoffees.com/our-story">Equator\r\n	Estate Coffees &amp; Teas</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li></ul></span>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">Many\r\nroasters mention transparency as a requirement for Fair Trade (and\r\nother) certifications:</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><ul><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>Democratic\r\n	and&nbsp;transparent&nbsp;organizations.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.allegrocoffee.com/about/our-story/our-story#faq">Allegro\r\n	Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)\r\n	(</font></i></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="https://www.armeno.com/store/coffees.aspx">Armeno\r\n	Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>Certification\r\n	is one primary vehicle for accountability, assurance\r\n	and&nbsp;transparency.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="https://www.alpensierracoffee.com/blog/sustainable-coffee-certified-or-not/">Alpen\r\n	Sierra</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>In\r\n	2008, we launched our third-party certified Counter Culture Direct\r\n	Trade Certification, which established direct trade standards for\r\n	sustainability, fairness, quality, andtransparency&nbsp;in the\r\n	coffee chain.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="https://counterculturecoffee.com/contact/about-us">Counter\r\n	Culture</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>The\r\n	certification process required us to answer a series of questions\r\n	that demonstratetransparency&nbsp;and accountability in our\r\n	financial records and supply chain, and consideration of workers,\r\n	the community, and the environment in our decision making.‚Äù\r\n	(</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.equatorcoffees.com/our-story">Equator\r\n	Estate Coffees &amp; Teas</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>C.A.F.E.\r\n	Practices includes guidelines in four key areas: quality, economic\r\n	accountability and&nbsp;transparency, social responsibility and\r\n	environmental leadership. Economictransparency&nbsp;is required.‚Äù\r\n	(</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.starbucks.com/responsibility/sourcing/coffee">Starbucks</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li></ul></font>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">One\r\nroaster flips this switch and mentions transparency in a critique of\r\nFair Trade:</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in">\r\n	<span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font color="#443f3f">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>Another\r\n	flaw of fair trade is its lack of&nbsp;transparency.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="https://www.theroasterie.com/blog/does-fair-trade-coffee-hold-up-to-its-name/">The\r\n	Roasterie</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font></span></p>\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">For\r\na few roasters, transparency is built into the requirements for\r\nwinning a&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.goodfoodawards.org/coffee/">Good\r\nFood Award</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">:</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><ul><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>To\r\n	qualify for entry, roasters and coffee farmers must emphasize\r\n	fairness and&nbsp;transparencyfrom seed to cup, and be using third\r\n	party certified organic beans.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.49thparallelroasters.com/blogs/news/4351962-organic-coffees">49th\r\n	Parallel Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>Finalists\r\n	attested to responsible production by detailing their efforts to\r\n	eliminate or reduce pesticides, herbicides and chemical fertilizers,\r\n	source ingredients locally where possible, implement water and\r\n	energy conservation, ensure traceability to the farm level, practice\r\n	good animal husbandry and exercise fair and&nbsp;transparent&nbsp;treatment\r\n	of workers and suppliers.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.evansbrotherscoffee.com/blog/evans-brothers-coffee-named-a-winner-of-prestigious-good-food-awards">Evans\r\n	Brothers Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>In\r\n	addition to the results of the cupping, in order for coffees to\r\n	qualify for the award, the producers and roasters needed to\r\n	emphasize fairness and&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;from seed to cup.‚Äù\r\n	(</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.ptscoffee.com/90-coffee-reviews/we-are-good-food-awards-finalists">PT''s\r\n	Coffee Roasting Co.</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li></ul></font>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">However,\r\nmost of the conversation around pricing transparency emphasizes its\r\nrole in the relationships that are part of a growing Direct Trade\r\ncoffee movement:&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p><p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f"><br></font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><ul><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>Barefoot\r\n	is able to source high quality coffee that is indicative of the\r\n	region and terroir, and you the customer can take part in helping to\r\n	empower these farmers to become self sufficient and strengthen the\r\n	ties of&nbsp;transparency.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.barefootcoffee.com/products/yirgacheffe-kochere">Barefoot\r\n	Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>We\r\n	not only strive to develop relationships with the farmers to ensure\r\n	full&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;of the buying process, but these\r\n	relationships allow us to provide important feedback to the farmers\r\n	to let them know when they are producing a great crop of coffee.‚Äù\r\n	(</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://birdrockcoffee.com/philosophy/">Bird\r\n	Rock Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>We\r\n	work hard developing relationships in the sourcing process and we\r\n	offer absolutetransparency&nbsp;on each of our storied coffees.‚Äù\r\n	(</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://cqcoffeeroasters.com/pages/our-prime-directive">CQ\r\n	Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>We\r\n	strive for&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;in our coffee sourcing and have\r\n	developed strong relationships with the importers, co-ops and\r\n	farmers from whom we buy coffee.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="https://victrolacoffeeroasters.wordpress.com/page/2/">Victrola\r\n	Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li></ul></font>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">And,\r\nspecifically, its implications for delivering better prices that\r\nreward coffee growers for their investments in quality:</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><ul><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>The\r\n	premise is simple: Engage producers in the quality process, control\r\n	quality from tree to port, make it all transparent, and&nbsp;</i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><font color="#443f3f">pay\r\n	prices that reward outstanding results</font></u></i></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">.\r\n	Ourtransparency&nbsp;contract is an important tool that defines and\r\n	documents costs and profit across the chain of custody.‚Äù\r\n	(</font></i></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.intelligentsiacoffee.com/content/coffee-process">Intelligentsia\r\n	Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>We\r\n	seek to deliver the&nbsp;</i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><font color="#443f3f">highest\r\n	possible return to farmers</font></u></i></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;and\r\n	therefore, whenever possible, require our importers, exporters,\r\n	cooperatives and farmers to agree upon the financial distribution\r\n	prior to harvest and act&nbsp;transparently&nbsp;in the execution of\r\n	distribution, allowing us to monitor the committed delivery price to\r\n	the farmers. Open&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;is critical, therefore we\r\n	work with all participants in the chain to provide full disclosure\r\n	back to the farmer or cooperative.‚Äù (</font></i></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.klatchroasting.com/Direct_Trade_Coffee_s/42.htm">Klatch\r\n	Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>We\r\n	seek to deliver the&nbsp;</i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><font color="#443f3f">highest\r\n	possible return to farmers</font></u></i></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;and\r\n	require our importers, exporters, cooperatives and farmers to agree\r\n	upon the financial distribution prior to harvest and\r\n	act&nbsp;transparently&nbsp;in the execution of distribution,\r\n	allowing us to monitor the committed delivery price to the farmers.\r\n	All Direct Trade participants must be open to&nbsp;transparentdisclosure\r\n	of financial deliveries back to the individual farmers.‚Äù (</font></i></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.ptscoffee.com/learn/direct-trade-coffee">PT''s\r\n	Coffee Roasting Co.</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>While\r\n	there is no stamp or logo to differentiate a direct trade coffee in\r\n	the market, there is traceability,&nbsp;transparency, and quality.\r\n	This&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;secures a&nbsp;</i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><font color="#443f3f">fair\r\n	price for the farmer</font></u></i></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">and\r\n	a quality product for the consumer.‚Äù (</font></i></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="https://www.theroasterie.com/blog/responsible-coffee-usda-organic-vs-fair-trade-vs-direct-trade/">The\r\n	Roasterie</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>Direct\r\n	Trade is predicated on a few simple pillars: improving coffee\r\n	quality,&nbsp;</i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><font color="#443f3f">incentive\r\n	based rewards</font></u></i></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;to\r\n	the farmer and&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;of the supply chain.‚Äù\r\n	(</font></i></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://stumptowncoffee.com/education-overview/direct-trade/">Stumptown\r\n	Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>In\r\n	order to ensure the highest quality cup, and build truly sustainable\r\n	sourcing, we make partners and friends throughout the supply chain\r\n	so that we control quality in every step of coffee travel,&nbsp;</i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><font color="#443f3f">set\r\n	payment&nbsp;</font></u></i></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">in\r\n	a&nbsp;transparent&nbsp;way, reach out to communities around the\r\n	world, and ensure a high standard of farming practices.‚Äù (</font></i></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://templecoffee.com/farm-to-cup-sourcing/">Temple\r\n	Coffee and Tea</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú</font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><font color="#443f3f">Paying\r\n	a fair wage</font></u></i></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;for\r\n	high quality coffees is just one of the ways we\r\n	establish&nbsp;transparentrelationships based on trust and mutual\r\n	respect and allows coffee drinkers and coffee farmers to connect\r\n	with every cup.‚Äù (</font></i></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.thanksgivingcoffee.com/fairtrade">Thanksgiving\r\n	Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li></ul></font>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">The\r\nfollowing sentence succinctly captures a critical motivation of the\r\nTTC movement by stressing how transparency improves growers‚Äô\r\nleverage and frees green coffee negotiations from the harmful\r\nvolatility observed in commodity coffee markets:</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><ul><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in; color: rgb(68, 63, 63);">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>The\r\n	trading process is&nbsp;transparent; farmers gain bargaining power\r\n	through knowledge, and receive a fair price that is not vulnerable\r\n	to commodity market fluctuations.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://www.gimmecoffee.com/news/what-relationship-coffee#sthash.53gDkmaV.dpbs">Gimme!\r\n	Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><span style="color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">&nbsp;</span></li></ul></p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><span style="display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">As\r\nTTC followers know, roasters like&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#!Bird-Rock-Roasters-More-Transparency-Data/cvxy/552207740cf21933cd3bf7b3">Bird\r\nRock Coffee Roasters</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;and&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color="#0000ff"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><u><a href="http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#!Counter-Culture-Two-Years-of-Transparency-Reports/cvxy/554a8f670cf248741715cd5b">Counter\r\nCulture</a></u></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;take\r\nthe commitment to pricing transparency to the next level by\r\npublishing regular transparency reports. We aim to support these\r\ncommitments to transparency, and to help the sector make good on the\r\npromise and passion that are housed in the following statements:</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><ul><li><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">Going\r\n	forward, we are also moving towards an even greater level\r\n	of&nbsp;transparency.‚Äù (</font></i></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://birdrockcoffee.com/direct-trade-video/price-transparency/">Bird\r\n	Rock Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>Sustainability\r\n	and&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;are core values for us, and these\r\n	concepts guide every decision me make.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="https://counterculturecoffee.com/contact/about-us">Counter\r\n	Culture</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color="#443f3f" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;">‚Äú<font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i>Due\r\n	to the delicate balance of specifics, we must be vigilant ‚Äì we\r\n	must seek out direct andtransparent&nbsp;relationships with coffee\r\n	growing professionals throughout the world. Directness\r\n	and&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;are important to us.‚Äù (</i></font></font></font><font color="#0000ff" style="font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font face="Helvetica, serif"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><u><a href="http://cqcoffeeroasters.com/pages/our-storied-coffees">CQ\r\n	Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face="Helvetica, serif" style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font style="font-size: 14pt"><i><font color="#443f3f">)</font></i></font></font><br></li></ul></font>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in"><font color="#443f3f">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<i style="font-family: Helvetica, serif; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><ol><li><i style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;"><font color="#443f3f">This\r\n	was done using a Google search option that supports searches within\r\n	specific websites. For example, ‚Äòtransparent site:\r\n	counterculturecoffee.com‚Äô or ‚Äòtransparency site:\r\n	birdrockcoffeeroasters.com.‚Äô</font></i><br></li></ol></i>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br>\r\n\r\n</p>\r\n<p align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br>\r\n\r\n</p>', NULL, '2015-06-17 15:25:13', 9),
(19, 'Specialty Coffee Retail Price Index ‚Äì 2015, Q2', 'specialty-coffee-retail-price-index-2015-q2', '<span style="line-height:1.5em;"><span style="font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;">In the second quarter of 2015, the&nbsp;<span style="text-decoration:underline;"><a href="http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#%21scrpi2/c1fos" target="_self">Specialty Coffee Retail Price Index (SCRPI)</a></span>&nbsp;rose\r\n by 1.5%.[1] The average price for roasted specialty coffee at the end \r\nof June, 2015 was $21.94 per pound. This breaks down into an average of \r\n$16.15 per pound for the lowest-priced coffees (-0.1%), and $27.73 for \r\nthe highest-priced coffees (+2.5%) sold on the websites of the SCRPI \r\nroasters.<br><br><img src="http://i.imgur.com/8FHyQZM.jpg" width="791"><br></span></span>', '<span style="line-height:1.5em;"><span style="font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;">In the second quarter of 2015, the&nbsp;<span style="text-decoration:underline;"><a href="http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#%21scrpi2/c1fos" target="_self">Specialty Coffee Retail Price Index (SCRPI)</a></span>&nbsp;rose\r\n by 1.5%.[1] The average price for roasted specialty coffee at the end \r\nof June, 2015 was $21.94 per pound. This breaks down into an average of \r\n$16.15 per pound for the lowest-priced coffees (-0.1%), and $27.73 for \r\nthe highest-priced coffees (+2.5%) sold on the websites of the SCRPI \r\nroasters.<br><br><img src="http://i.imgur.com/KVu6P9c.jpg" width="791"><br></span></span><br><p style="line-height: 1.5em;" class="font_8"><span style="line-height:1.5em;"><span style="font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;">The\r\n year-over-year increase in specialty coffee prices ‚Äì from the second \r\nquarter of 2014 to the second quarter of 2015 ‚Äì was 12.5%. This broke \r\ndown into a 1.1% increase for the lowest-priced coffees, and a 20.9% \r\nincrease for the highest-priced coffees.</span></span></p><p style="line-height: 1.5em;" class="font_8"><span style="line-height:1.5em;"><span style="font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;">Note that the corresponding&nbsp;<span style="text-decoration:underline;"><a href="http://www.ico.org/prices/p2.htm" target="_blank">ICO Composite Price</a></span>&nbsp;for\r\n green coffee fell to $1.25 per pound in June, 2015. Thus, while retail \r\nprices for specialty coffees continued to rise, commodity prices fell \r\nanother 1.7% during the second quarter. Year-over-year, average retail \r\nprices for specialty coffees increased by 12.7%, while the ICO Composite\r\n Price fell by 17.8%</span></span></p><p class="font_8"><b><span style="font-family:helvetica-w01-bold,helvetica-w02-bold,helvetica-lt-w10-bold,sans-serif;">Supplementary Analysis ‚Äì Naming Coffee Growers</span></b></p><span style="line-height:1.5em;"><span style="font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;">While\r\n collecting 2015, Q2 SCRPI price data, we documented whether the name of\r\n the producing farm, farmer or cooperative was specifically mentioned on\r\n the web page that marketed each coffee. For example, when Blue Bottle \r\nCoffee sold its <span style="text-decoration:underline;"><a href="https://bluebottlecoffee.com/store/brazil-faf-santa-clara-red-catuai-natural" target="_blank">Brazil FAF Santa Clara Red Catuai Natural</a></span> coffee, customers were told that ‚Äúin the highlands of Divinolandia, Brazil, <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Milton Nogueira, the esteemed producer of Santa Clara estate</span>, cares for his red Catuai coffee variety trees with a lot of pride.‚Äù<br><br></span></span><p style="line-height: 1.5em; text-align: justify;" class="font_8"><span style="line-height:1.5em;"><span style="font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;">How\r\n prevalent is this practice of naming coffee growers? More than 60% (36 \r\nout of 58) of the highest-priced coffee listings in the 2015, Q2 SCRPI \r\nmentioned coffee growers by name. This percentage was just 12% (7 out of\r\n 58) for the lowest-priced coffee listings. The difference is explained \r\nin part by the fact that 44 out of the 58 lowest-priced coffees are \r\nblends and espressos, compared to only nine of the 58 highest-priced \r\ncoffees.</span></span></p><p style="line-height: 1.5em; text-align: justify;" class="font_8"><span style="line-height:1.5em;"><span style="font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;">This\r\n suggests that a non-trivial number of coffee growers are being \r\nrecognized for the work that they do, and that this practice is more \r\ncommon among the more highly-valued coffees.</span></span></p><p style="line-height: 1.5em; text-align: justify;" class="font_8"><span style="line-height:1.5em;"><span style="font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;">Does\r\n the specialty coffee market value knowing the identity of the coffee \r\ngrower? The following chart suggest that it does, but only at the high \r\nend of the market. Among the lowest-priced coffees in the 2015, Q2 \r\nSCRPI, the seven that made specific reference to the grower sold for an \r\naverage of $16.25 per pound, a $0.11 (0.7%) premium over the other \r\nlowest-priced coffees. Among the highest-priced coffees, the 36 that \r\nspecifically named the grower sold for an average of $29.99 per pound; \r\n$5.98 (24.9%) more than the average charged for the other highest-priced\r\n coffees.</span></span></p><img src="http://i.imgur.com/JV7U1nH.jpg" width="688"><br><br><span style="line-height:1.5em;"><span style="font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;">These\r\n observations confirm that there is a tangible interest within the \r\nspecialty coffee market in knowing where coffees are coming from and who\r\n is growing the beans. Moreover, this willingness to name and charge \r\npremiums for specific coffee growers intensifies as we move from the \r\nlower to the higher end of the specialty coffee market.</span></span><br>', NULL, '2015-07-15 08:31:51', 8);

